STANDARD UNIX STREAMS

Under the normal circumstances, every Unix program has three streams (files) opened for it when it starts up

stdin : This is referred to as 'standard input' and the associated file descriptor is 0. Represented also as 'STDIN'. The Unix program will read the default input form STDIN.

stdout : This is referred to as 'standard output' and the associated file descriptor is 1. This is represented as STDOUT. The Unix program will write the default output at STDOUT

stderr : This is referred to as the 'standard error' and the associated file descriptor is 2. This is also represented as STDERR. The Unix program will write all the error messages at STDERR.

