When the shell window is opened, it undergoes a phase called initialization to set up the environment. This is usually a two-step process that involves reading the following
-'/etc/profile'
-'./profile'
-'.bashrc'

The above process is as follows:
-The shell checks  to see whether the file '/etc/profile' exists
-If it exists, the shell reads it. Otherwise, this file is skipped and no error message is displayed
-The shell checks to see whether the file .profile exists in the home directory
-If it exists, then the shell reads it. Otherwise, it will skip and no error message is displayed.
-As soon as these files have been read, the shell displays the prompt and the commands then typed can be executed.


THE .profile FILE

-The file '/etc/profile' is maintained by the system administrator and contains shell initialization information required by all the users on that system.

-The file .profile is under your control and you can add as much as customisation information you want to this file. It includes 
-the type of teminal you are using
-A list of directories in which to locate the commands
-A list of varibale affecting the look and fell of the terminal

-.profile is located in the 'Home' directory of the system.

SETTING THE TERMINAL TYPE

Terminal is automatically configured by either the logic or getty programs. In incorrectly configured, set the terminal to the lowest common denominator as below
'TERM=vt100'

SETTING THE PATH

***Before executing the command on the terminal, The system has to locate
the command or the source through which it can be run.

